segments.text: First of March, chatting with Dick Hervey in his study and we're going to talk about his student days and now I'm going to stop the machine and check and hope that it's working.
Dick, you grew up in Greenville.
Why did you come to Texas A&M?
What were the factors that led you here instead of somewhere else?
I came to A&M because of the tradition of a number of Greenville young men who came to A&M before me.
And every one of those young men that came here before me, I admired very much.
I had a football scholarship to go to Texas Tech.
I was planning to go to Texas Tech because my older brother had gone to Texas Tech.
I had an uncle who owned a drug store in Lubbock.
I could work part-time and make a little money.
But when it came down to the, close to the end, I told my mother that I was going to go to Texas Tech.
And I never regretted it today in my life because I had a wonderful student experience.
Did you come and visit before you came?
I never saw this campus until I came in here with a fellow named Jim Atkinson.
Came in here in a yellow convertible and I came with him very impressed by that bag.
What year was that?
I matriculated with about
Around 15 other young men from Great Wilkins came here in the fall of 1938.
Alright, y'all came in a convertible.
What did you bring in the way of baggage?
I brought one footlocker.
One green footlocker that had everything pretty well that I owned and I had some space left in it.
So it wasn't very heavy.
But I had been told what to bring and so I had it all pretty well marked with my name in it and so forth.
I didn't have any uniform.
I came here and I had a little money that I could buy what I needed.
And the main thing that we wore
The first week that we were here were white coveralls in a campaign.
This campus was a sea of white coveralls.
The white coveralls with the buttons all the way up down the front.
In the back it said Texas Aggies had been across the back.
And so the white coveralls were new to all of us.
We had about 2,500 freshmen in our class.
And the campaign hats were new to us.
And also, the number one thing on the campus around the class buildings were lines.
Standing in line for everything.
It was a line.
Everywhere you went, you knew there was going to be a line.

So you could just see these snake-like lines meandering around the classroom buildings, and all these freshmen trying to get registered and so forth, standing in line with white coveralls and campaign pants, all of them just lying.
Now, this fellow that you came down with, he had already been at A&M.
He was a senior.
So he knew where to take you to get...
He knew where to let me out.
He was in the band hall, and my friend Jay Atkinson, who was also a first cousin of this fellow's, came with us.
He was going to apply for the band, and so I was assigned to Goodman Hall.
I was assigned to C Company Infantry.
But when we came, he drove right to Bazell Hall and unloaded us all.
I don't know where he parked his car.
How did you get designated to C Company?
I had requested an assignment to C Company because a lot of the Greenville boys were in C Company.
And that's where I was.
Did you have any idea what your major might be?
I took pre-med.
I enrolled in a pre-med course.
until the end of my freshman year.
And I decided I didn't like the sciences.
So I took geology for another semester.
At the end of the second semester, I didn't like geology.
So I went to Colonel Eichasch, who was assistant to the president.
And he was one of the great engineers.
And I advised him, I said, Colonel, I don't like, I didn't like pre-med now.
I've gone a semester in geology and I don't know what it looks like.
He said, well, what are you going to do when you get out?
I said, I want to be in business somewhere.
He said, well, go over there and sign up for marketing and finance.
So I went to see Mr. Dean.
And he took all over my course records and said, well, why don't you major in marketing and finance?
You'll be a generalist.
You'll be able to do pretty well anything in my business.
So I did.
And due to these two changes in courses, I had to take a lot of extra hours my last
what my last four semesters to graduate on schedule, but I did without ever having to go to summer school.
Describe the campus physically when you got here in 38.
What major buildings were where?
Well, the academic building was the central point.
The drill field
was there in front of the MSC.
But the MSC wasn't there.
The MSC was not there.
Around that block where the MSC was, was campus faculty housing.
The military wall, which extended from the Dine Hall to Samisa Hall, was pretty well the center of the
campus with buildings on both the east side military wall and the west side military wall.
And the administration building at the east gate had just been finished not too long before I came.
The university had just been turned around facing west and facing east when they built the
So, my world revolved around the drill field, Goodman Hall, Goodell Hall, the YMCA, which is right there by the most air wall.
And then the dorms in that area, which were growing per year.
And back over here was Hart Hall.
had been converted to a military building.
It had been a dormitory.
And the combat's office was that area, and the tank officers had offices in that building.
I didn't have much business there as a freshman and sophomore when I became a junior.
We had quite a bit of business as students.
But the west campus, the only thing across the Welborn Road was two railroad depots and the creamery and the horse barns.
polo fields, they practiced polo over there somewhere, and they had polo horses over there, across there, where they had the cavalry horses, and the artillery horses, all across the railroad.
That was about all that was over there.
What kind of impression did this campus make on you?
The campus made a tremendous impression on me.
All the dormitories were, that dining hall was absolutely awesome.
We sat up in that main big room, no air conditioning or anything, but they had ceiling fans on the pedestals.
And I don't know how many they had in there, but they had a lot of them.
And to see, march in, we marched in and found a bunch of walls.
And we marked right in the main entrance, right at the end of the military wall, our receipt company.
We had tables right by one of the major doors coming from the kitchen.
And to see all those students march into that thing and go to their respective tables and sit down with something unbelievable, it was really impressive.
And I had not been ever much of a military person except for a scout.
was the only kind of regimented program I'd ever been in.
And going in the Corps and marching and learning to carry a rifle and all that was new, very much new.
You are issued uniforms.
We were issued uniforms.
And what about your haircut, that first haircut?
Well, that first haircut, we went to the YMCA.
I had, it didn't bother me much.
You know, we, I played football, I had burr haircuts all the time.
In the spring and the fall, the early fall of the year before the workout, we had to go get our hair burred.
And so, we did the same thing.
However, we didn't have to get hair cut as short as they had.
We didn't have to get our hair just cut way off.
Do you have any idea what a haircut cost?
Somewhere around 35 to 50 cents.
Tell me about what it was like to be a freshman in the dormitory.
Was there hazing?
What was the routine?
Well, it was just kind of awesome.
I had been warned about what to expect, and I had been warned about the haste, the ESX haste.
It was a good experience.
First place, they said the South Boards made lots of messages and stuff.
sophomores would have a meeting with the freshmen.
They called them bleed meetings, bleed sessions.
And there, they didn't have this Aggie, whatever they called it, where you had to learn all the dorms and everything.
That wasn't much in the picture at that time.
But the primary thrust was, freshmen, you've got to know every person in this company.
You've got to know their name.
where their hometown was.
That's the first thing you've got to learn.
And also you've got to know where Casey's is so you can run details.
Go there and get a coat of coat or something.
I never had much trouble remembering names.
I was pretty good at remembering names.
When they said you've got to learn everybody's name, I got to thinking.
And they'd test us.
They'd get up and say, freshman
Who is this?
Who is that?
Where is he from?
Where is he from?
And they'd try to excite you and make you, upset you and everything.
But we all had to go through that process.
And we had to, they said, you gotta shake hands with everybody you see.
You gotta speak to everybody you see.
You gotta shake hands.
If you don't know them, you gotta shake hands and say, I'm Fish Hervey.
And you gotta speak to everybody.
And then when they felt like they had hazed us a little bit, like beating butt-wise, they told us there was going to be an Airbus and they did.
What was the, what kind of paddle or instrument did they use?
They had handmade paddles.
They were about this long.
I've got one out in the country.
They've got one about, they're about this long with a handle part.
And then they were about that wide and about the size of a 1x4 board.
A little smaller than a 1x4 board.
Now, some people say, oh, he beat me to death with a baseball bat or something like that.
But I never saw a baseball bat.
They were paddles.
And hell, I was so little and pretty muscular.
And hell, they'd say, get a pooch.
I'd get a pooch.
And they'd beat me all day.
It wouldn't hurt me too bad after I caught on to how to handle them.
Let's go back to dormitory life.
Was your freshman roommate a special person in your life?
My freshman year, I had two roommates.
One was a fellow named Ross Meredith.
He came from Dallas.
He was kind of a hell-raising character, full of life, full of him and bigger, and not very studious.
And my
other roommate was Whit Stockley who came from Marion, Arkansas.
His people were cotton farmers in the Mississippi Valley and he was rather quiet and had a deep south voice but was not a very good student and the three of us
got along well, enjoyed each other.
But three in a small room in Vibram Hall just was not conducive to very good study.
We had three bunk beds, three, one, two, three, stacked like that.
I think Wood slept on the top bunk.
Ross slept on the bottom because he was a big fella.
and I slept on the middle bunk.
How did y'all determine who got what bunk originally?
I don't remember.
I don't remember how we decided that.
We had each had a study table.
Yeah, describe that room.
Yeah, we had three study tables.
We all had to go buy us a lamp.
That was one of the first things we had to do was buy a lamp.
It was a round lamp, a desk lamp, kind of like that.
And we had a book rack that was more or less homemade by somebody around here.
And they sold it.
I think they sold it for about $2 or $3.
You put this book rack back here on the back of your study table and that's where you kept your books and so forth.
And another thing you had to have was wooden shower shoes.
because we used, we walked barefooted a lot.
None of us had a house that never did use them.
So we walked in the halls all the time down to the showers and we had to keep from getting athlete's foot.
So we all had a big bottle of Benzoyn or something to put on our feet if we got a touch of athlete's foot by treating ourselves.
Now the restroom and shower facilities were down the hallway.
Yes.
In a gang fashion.
In a gang fashion, that's right.
Just like a barracks, army barracks.
Describe a typical freshman day, Monday through Saturday.
What time did y'all get up and what time did you do?
Well, we got up about six.
We had to clean our own room.
And then about seven, a little before, we had to go into our rooms where we were room-marking.
See, we all had to clean up somebody else's room, too.
So I cleaned up Darcy McCurry and Jack Henderson's room.
Bill Amickson and I did.
Bill was my next-door neighbor.
And the seniors had two room-markings.
And we'd go into their room until about 7 in the morning.
We'd wake them up.
And then get up and we'd start to clean up.
And then, boy, it must have been earlier than that because we had to fall in and march to Subesa Hall.
And we had to be out of there at the first class at 8 o'clock.
So I guess all that got to move that up a little bit or move back a little bit.
Anyway, once we got rid of doing our little chores like making unfurling rooms and our upperclassmen's rooms, we just had one room.
At a certain time in the morning, we'd fall in out on the military walk.
And then we could hear the commands up and down the military walk when we were ready to start marching.
We'd start marching in.
And we marched into the dining hall and ate at a regular place, the same tables every day.
But after we finished eating breakfast, we were free to just walk back out as we wanted to.
What was a typical breakfast menu?
Well, a typical menu was scrambled eggs, bacon or sausage, and Dunwaden, we called it bread, rolls, or toast.
coffee, milk, we didn't drink much coffee in those days.
They served milk in those little bottles, old fashioned bottles, and like that, came from the dairy, and we each would, we could drink as many of those as we wanted in the dining hall.
Not supposed to take them out, but we just took them out all the time for our upperclassmen.
We said, bring me a bottle of milk, and we'd do that.
When we finished breakfast, we'd go to the post office, walk to the post office.
We all had mailboxes in the post office there, where it is now.
And we'd check our own boxes.
Sometimes we'd check other people's boxes.
Then we'd go home and get our books and stock device.
We'd be in class normally most of the morning, Monday, Wednesdays and Fridays, you know, just whatever your schedule was.
But we'd get back to the dorm and fall in again and march to the mess hall, dining hall.
After the lunch, we'd walk back and
go back to our dorms and get our books and head off for our afternoon classes.
We had drills on Thursday, which was ROTC day.
We had a drill every Thursday.
And that was from 1 o'clock in the afternoon until 5.
And we had classes on Saturday morning.
Nothing in the afternoon Saturday.
We had noon through the third.
that at night, about whatever time it was, we'd fall in again for our evening meal, and when we took you over, we came back to the YMCA, the front steps of the YMCA, where they had the jail practice.
And we stayed there until the jail practice was over, which by then was dark, it was dark.
And then we went home, back to the dorms, and then hit the rooms and studied.
And then the lights out?
The lights were out about 10.30.
Did you have any late afternoon free time except on Saturdays and Sundays?
Depending on your schedule.
What would you do during those unscheduled hours?
What I did, usually if I had say, if I had as much as two hours, I'd go to the library.
We'd paddle around, we'd spend a lot of time over at the athletic department, we'd spend a lot of time at the gym.
We'd go to the gym and do something.
We'd wrestle or we'd box or we'd play handball.
I spent almost all of my time when I wasn't involved or told to be doing something in the library.
Not doing research or anything, but just studying and all that.
Did anybody ever go to sleep in the library?
All the time.
Oh.
All the time.
Did anybody bother?
No.
Oh.
No.
You see, they had a rule that we could not take a nap.
We were going at such pace that we would just become exhausted.
And I would go to the, many times I would go to the library and just lay down on the big table and just go to sleep.
I never was.
Now I had trouble a few times going to sleep in class because I just was exhausted.
I remember old Major Orr woke me up one time and asked me to answer a question.
And I didn't know what the question was, but I said, Major, would you please repeat the question?
Something about good hygiene.
I don't know.
Anyway, once he repeated the question, I could answer it, but I was asleep.
Describe the mealtime routine for lunch or supper.
for a fish?
Well, a fish had to do all the waiting on the quality of the classic.
They had to see that they could be served with the main meal of the day, like fried chicken.
See that they had the mashed potatoes.
See that they had the gravy on it.
See that they haven't done the water and sugar and all of that.
Once they all got served, then us fish could eat.
We had to wait until all the other classes, sophomore, junior, senior.
Did you all then sometimes remain in the dining hall at the table when they finished?
Yes.
Then you could eat.
Then we could eat more than we could have otherwise.
But they would keep bringing us food.
We never were without food.
Sometime we would sharpen desserts.
because they did serve us a lot of desserts, and sometimes the upper classes would take part of the pies out of the dining hall.
What were your favorite dishes?
Well, I liked the fried chicken, and they served a lot of it until I finally burned out on it because they didn't serve so much of it.
But all that food they served was good.
Was there anything that you remember you didn't like?
I don't remember that.
They served, mostly I remember the bread was a sort of a roll.
It had plenty of butter.
It had iced tea.
It had milk.
And breakfast they served eggs, pancakes, and bacon, sausage, and coffee.
And I think orange juice.
And it was every meal was seated.
Every meal was seated.
Let's try to record as much as we can of the chow hall slang.
Oh, okay.
I was just thinking about some of that.
Let me think.
Well, rabbit was salad.
That was the letters.
Salt and pepper was sand dame.
Salt and pepper sand dame.
Ketchup was what?
Bud, buddy.
Pass the buddy.
Any dessert was kush.
Milk.
Milk was what?
Cow.
Cow.
Cow.
Yeah, and bull, bull, bull neck, bull meat, bull neck, about the size of a bull neck, was the meat.
And, uh.
Tea?
Tea was what?
Was that horse?
Could have been.
There was something.
Yeah, yeah.
Let's see, you mentioned bread was.
Bread was gunwale.
Gunwale.
And sugar was what?
Let's see.
Beans.
Beans.
That was... Oh, yeah, there's something for beans like blowout.
Corn.
Corn.
Beans.
Oh, it had to be something like
Do you remember any, when you were finishing, do you remember any dining hall tricks or pranks?
They were playing pranks all the time in the dining hall.
and that usually was an assigned chore that somebody had to do.
For example, sometimes they'd designate some freshman to act like a moody bird and fly over the
play like he was flying and he'd go over and get right in front of somebody and just flap his wings and do something crazy like that.
And they were just practical jokes at that time.
Did y'all ever, did they ever pull any prank off on a sophomore or a junior?
Yeah, yeah.
If he looked away, did anybody ever put any?
Oh yeah, oh yeah.
Yeah, they were putting this
Let's see, with your outfit, did your outfit have a nickname?
Yes, C-Company.
C-Company, okay, so it worked.
After the 12 new dormitories were built, they moved me out of C Company and moved me into K Company.
I was in dorm 3, and I lived in dorm 3 for then 3 years, which was in what we called the new area.
Now the new area opened in?
In the beginning of our sophomore year.
And how did those dormitories seem to y'all compared to what you had first year?
They seemed good?
They seemed good.
In the first place, they were all on one level.
They still had the four flights up and down, but they had two sections of bathrooms on each floor, one on one end of the building, one on the other.
One wide, about seven feet wide hall, right down the middle.
a stair at one end of the building, another stair at the other end of the building.
And they had one trouble with them.
